  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Poland have a digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not exactly. Poland doesn't have a dedicated DNV like Croatia or Portugal. Instead, freelancers use the self-employment route—registering a JDG business and obtaining a visa for business purposes. This offers unique advantages (work with Polish clients, path to PR) but requires full business integration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are the income requirements for Poland's freelance visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Poland has no strict income minimum—just proof of sufficient means (approximately €850/month). This is much lower than typical DNV requirements of €2,500-3,500/month. However, you'll pay ZUS contributions regardless of income, so factor those into your budget.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work with Polish clients on this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes—this is a unique advantage of Poland's system. Unlike most DNV programs that restrict you to foreign clients only, your JDG registration allows you to invoice Polish and foreign clients alike. This opens the door to the local market.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How much are ZUS contributions?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          ZUS varies by stage: ~€100/month during Ulga na start (first 6 months), ~€150-200/month during Mały ZUS (next 24 months), then ~€300-400/month at full rate. First-time freelancers save significantly in their first 2.5 years.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get permanent residency through freelancing?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. After 5 years of continuous legal residence in Poland (including on temporary residence permits for business), you can apply for permanent residence. This is a major advantage over most DNV programs that don't offer PR pathways.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Polish?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not required for the visa, but helpful for daily life. Major cities (Warsaw, Kraków, Wrocław) have good English infrastructure, and many accountants work with English-speaking foreigners. Learning basic Polish improves quality of life significantly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

